      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! Over the last decade, the expansion of the social safety net has had a nuanced impact on labor participation rates. On one hand, some studies suggest that enhanced unemployment benefits and social welfare programs may have reduced the immediate urgency to seek employment, thereby slightly decreasing labor participation rates, particularly among young and low-skilled workers. However, in the long term, these expansions have provided a more stable economic foundation, potentially facilitating job searches and leading to higher quality employment and better overall well-being. As a result, the net effect on labor participation is complex and varies across different demographics and countries.",
